            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>What is the Schwarzschild radius?</h2>
              <p>
                The Schwarzschild radius \(R_s\) is the radius of the event
                horizon of a non-rotating, uncharged black hole. If an object's
                mass is compressed within this radius, the escape velocity at
                its surface equals the speed of light, and not even light can
                escape its gravity.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Schwarzschild radius formula</p>
                <p>\[ R_s = \frac{2GM}{c^2} \]</p>
                <p class="text-sm mb-0">where:</p>
                <ul class="text-sm">
                  <li>\(R_s\) = Schwarzschild radius (m)</li>
                  <li>
                    \(G\) = gravitational constant \(6.67430 \times
                    10^{-11}\,\text{m}^3\text{kg}^{-1}\text{s}^{-2}\)
                  </li>
                  <li>\(M\) = mass of the object (kg)</li>
                  <li>
                    \(c\) = speed of light \(2.99792458 \times
                    10^{8}\,\text{m/s}\)
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>Inverting the formula: radius → mass</h3>
              <p>
                If you know the Schwarzschild radius and want the corresponding
                mass, solve for \(M\):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">\[ M = \frac{R_s c^2}{2G} \]</div>

              <h2>Typical Schwarzschild radii</h2>
              <p>
                The radius scales linearly with mass. A useful rule of thumb is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ R_s \approx 2.95 \,\text{km} \times
                \left(\frac{M}{M_\odot}\right) \]
              </div>
              <p>Some examples:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>1 solar mass</strong> black hole: \(R_s \approx 2.95\)
                  km
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>10 solar masses</strong>: \(R_s \approx 29.5\) km
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>4 million solar masses</strong> (Milky Way’s Sgr A*):
                  \(R_s \approx 11.8\) million km
                </li>
                <li><strong>Earth’s mass</strong>: \(R_s \approx 8.9\) mm</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Worked example: Schwarzschild radius of the Sun</h2>
              <p>
                Take the Sun’s mass \(M_\odot = 1.98847 \times
                10^{30}\,\text{kg}\).
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Compute \(2GM\): \[ 2GM = 2 \times 6.67430\times10^{-11}
                  \times 1.98847\times10^{30} \approx
                  2.654\times10^{20}\,\text{m}^3\text{s}^{-2} \]
                </li>
                <li>
                  Compute \(c^2\): \[ c^2 = (2.99792458\times10^{8})^2 \approx
                  8.98755\times10^{16}\,\text{m}^2\text{s}^{-2} \]
                </li>
                <li>
                  Divide: \[ R_s = \frac{2GM}{c^2} \approx
                  \frac{2.654\times10^{20}}{8.98755\times10^{16}} \approx
                  2.95\times10^{3}\,\text{m} = 2.95\,\text{km} \]
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                So if the Sun were compressed into a sphere of radius about 3
                km, it would become a black hole. Its actual radius is about
                696,000 km, far larger than its Schwarzschild radius.
              </p>

              <h2>Assumptions and limitations</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The formula applies to
                  <strong>non-rotating, uncharged</strong> (Schwarzschild) black
                  holes.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Real astrophysical black holes usually rotate (Kerr black
                  holes), which modifies the horizon structure.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Quantum gravity effects near the singularity are not included;
                  this is a classical general relativity result.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>Does every object have a Schwarzschild radius?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. For any mass \(M\), you can compute a Schwarzschild radius
                \(R_s = 2GM/c^2\). Most objects are much larger than their
                Schwarzschild radius, so they are not black holes.
              </p>

              <h3>Is the Schwarzschild radius the “size” of the black hole?</h3>
              <p>
                It is the radius of the <strong>event horizon</strong>, the
                boundary beyond which nothing can escape. It is not a solid
                surface. The central singularity (in the classical picture) has
                no spatial extent.
              </p>

              <h3>Can the Schwarzschild radius be observed directly?</h3>
              <p>
                We infer it indirectly from the black hole’s mass (e.g., via
                stellar orbits or accretion dynamics). High-resolution imaging
                (like the Event Horizon Telescope) can resolve structures on the
                scale of a few \(R_s\), but not the horizon itself as a sharp
                edge.
              </p>

              <h3>What happens inside the Schwarzschild radius?</h3>
              <p>
                Inside the event horizon, all future-directed paths lead toward
                the singularity. In classical general relativity, nothing
                (including light) can escape once it crosses \(R_s\). A full
                description likely requires a theory of quantum gravity, which
                is still an open problem.
              </p>
